This is probably one of the least expensive "food by the pound" buffets you can visit in FiDi.  I'm basing this review solely on the basement buffet, I've never visited the upstairs restaurant. The space is usually very clean and there are at least 3 cashiers available during the lunch rush hour to hurry you out of the place.  The food is typical chinese restaurant cuisine, but they also have a vast selection of steamed veggies and salad dishes for those who want to eat light.  There are food attendants on the floor most of the time so the food gets replenished on the regular.  They have seating upstairs so you can get your food, get on the elevator and eat in their upstairs dining area.  I suggest you look around the entire buffet before you begin filling up your container.  It'll help you make better decisions and spend less.  Highly recommend.

This is one of my favourite Chinese places in the financial district. There's a huge buffet selection in the basement that charges by weight. As well as Chinese selections there are also some salad selections too. You should be able to find something you like.  On the first floor they have counter service, with a smaller selection of items. Though they did recently add a gourmet noodle counter. And it serves won ton noodles - using proper won ton noodles. Although you can pick several other different types of noodles if you'd prefer, though you'd be WRONG! Proper won ton noodles should be a very specific thin, yellow egg noodle and it should also be al dente. Remarkably they, unlike a lot of Chinese places, use the right noodle and get the right texture. You can also have cha siu (roast pork) with the won ton noodles. I was a bit horrified at first that they did this as it's not traditional, but it actually makes the bowl very tasty as the won ton dumplings aren't that great. Note, it's a huge portion, you could easily share this between two people. Or just come hungry.  There's also a bubble tea stall in the front, which I've never tried. There's a large amount of seating upstairs and some seating on the first floor.  Get here before noon to get a discount and avoid the work lunch time crowds too.

It's fast and is basically a non-chain Panda Express. It is fast. They are options. The food tastes okay like any fried, breaded, fatty food will do. You get two items over rice for about $7, so it's one of the least expensive lunches around. The texture of the chicken makes me wonder whether it's real meat--it's hard to explain, but several of the pieces essentially gave me now chewing resistance. I also tried the paradise shrimp and it was okay. They have a credit card minimum of $8, which is just over the cost of a standard lunch meal. They have a small discount for late lunch or early lunch. It's actually a fairly comfortable and quit dining area in the main floor, and there's more seating on another floor. It's cheaper than nearby china chalet and actually not too much lower in quality.

I visit the downstairs lunch buffet regularly. The vegetables (especially string beans) are delicious, with just the right amount of crunch. Some of the noodles are very good too, without being drowned in sauces.  They have a huge selection, but I steer clear of the salty/sugary sauces, sushi and dumplings.  (No one does everything well.)  The price is right, with a discount after 1:45pm and free soda for purchases over $6.  The checkout process is very efficient; one woman weighs your food and bags it while another takes your money.  It's a great no-frills lunch spot.

I enjoy the buffet selection downstairs over the hot food bar they serve upstairs. You get to choose whatever you want and pay per pound. When you spend over a pound (its around $5.89/lb) you get a free can of soda with your purchase. Something I would recommend is to have a scale on the outside so that we can know how much we are spending because I tend to over do it since everything looks so good and I end up getting $8-9 worth of food. What I don't like about the hot food bar upstairs is that they tend to be a lot more greesy and too saucy for me. Either you specify less sauce or no sauce, then maybe it's better. There is a lot seating upstairs, but some times during busy hours, you might have to share your table with fellow customers. Overall, I think the food is pretty good, but it's sad that some of their prices went up.
